-- STOCKS NEWS US-Wary investors snap up double-leveraged fund TVIX
-- 
-- Mon May 05, 2014 09:18AM EDT
-- None



May 5 (Reuters) - With the market near record levels, investors bracing for a technical selloff in equities are snapping up volatility products to hedge against a decline.

In early morning trading on Monday, Credit Suisse AG - VelocityShares Daily 2x VIX Short Term ETNs <TVIX.O> are among the most actively traded securities, up 2.2 percent with more than 200,000 contracts changing hands. TVIX has lost nearly 20 percent of its value so far this year and over 90 percent in the last few years as the bull market roared. Industry data released on Friday showed equity fund managers trimmed their long positions while speculators trimmed their net shorts in S&P 500 futures contracts in the week ended April 29, according to the Commodity Futures Trading Commision. [ID:nEMS0D46GO]   Long  Short Net   -------------------------------------------  Fund Managers 296,38195,608   200,773 Speculators   106,527   168,982   -62,455 From earlier in the day: 08:32 - Target Corp <TGT.N> shares are climbing the most active list before the bell and are off 1.5 percent on news the retailer's Chief Executive and Chairman Gregg Steinhafel is leaving in the wake of the last year's devastating data breach. [ID:nL2N0NR0B5] Pfizer Inc <PFE.N> shares are also down in premarket action, off 0.8 percent after first-quarter results that were well below Wall Street expectations on falling sales of generic medicines. The company also said it may sweeten its offer for rival AstraZeneca. [ID:nL2N0NR094] For more on the day's premarket action click [XHR/US].  From earlier in the day: 08:02 - U.S. index futures are all lower Monday morning with the focus largely on overseas factors - more evidence of slowing momentum in the Chinese economy and escalating tension in Ukraine. * S&P 500 e-minis <ESc1> are down 7.25 points, about 0.39 percent, with about 120,000 contracts traded. * Nasdaq 100 e-minis <NQ1> are down 0.43 percent, or 15.25 points, on volume of nearly 23,000 contracts.